	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64431156"><p>I'm sure those are also benefits, but it mostly makes things faster because you don't have connectors in the way. Solder joints can be a pain for high speed, low power signals. Actual connectors are much worse, and if those connectors lead to off-board modules that's even worse. And actual connectors that are accessible without disassembling everything (i.e. the traces are likely even longer) worse yet.</p><p>First reply here has more detail:<br><span class="substr"> </span> <a href="https://electronics.stackexchange.com/questions/603157/lpddr-is-pluggable-socketed-not-soldered-connection-possible-for-low-voltage" title="stackexchange.com">https://electronics.stackexcha...</a> [stackexchange.com] </p></div>
	</div>

