<div id="comment_status_64431130" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64431130" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64431130" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64431130" name="comment_link_64431130" href="//hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23305826&amp;cid=64431130" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64431130)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64431130" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64431130); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~serviscope_minor">serviscope_minor</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~serviscope_minor">( 664417 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64431130"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64431130"><p>Until, well about now they has been no socketed form factor for LPDDR. SODIMM just doesn't have the electrical spec to slow for it. The impedance of the contacts is too variable for the very low voltages sand high frequencies. This is why the new form factor has a much higher contact pressure. Also it's easier to get consistent trace lengths which helps too.</p><p>This isn't a grand conspiracy, laptops with SODIMM have serious power draw penalties.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64431130">

